docs.lead_paragraph: MUNICH — Secretary of State Mike Pompeo appeared at an annual gathering of Western diplomats and business leaders to declare on Saturday that “the West is winning,’’ something that would be obvious to Trump administration critics, he said, if they were only willing to accept “reality.”

docs.abstract: With impeachment behind them and an eye on November, Democrats appear to have decided that focusing on President Trump’s norm-shattering words and deeds only elevates him.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — House Democrats, recovering from their failed push to remove President Trump from office, are making a sharp pivot to talking about health care and economic issues, turning away from their investigations of the president as they focus on preserving their majority.

headline.main: Democrats Plan to Highlight Health Care and Jobs Over Investigating Trump
headline.print_headline: Democrats, Rebuffed on Impeachment, Pivot to Health Care and Jobs

docs.abstract: Immigrants are critical to expanding the United States’ labor pool. Mick Mulvaney acknowledged that, even if President Trump’s policies do not.
docs.snippet: Immigrants are critical to expanding the United States’ labor pool. Mick Mulvaney acknowledged that, even if President Trump’s policies do not.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — At a private event last week, Mick Mulvaney, the acting White House chief of staff, stated a reality that economists treat as conventional wisdom but that the Trump administration routinely ignores: The United States needs immigration to fuel future economic growth.

headline.main: Why a Top Trump Aide Said ‘We Are Desperate’ for More Immigrants
headline.print_headline: ‘We Are Desperate’  For More Immigrants,  A Top Trump Aide Says

docs.abstract: The former New York City mayor laid out his views on the scope and limits of presidential authority and potential post-Trump curbs.
docs.snippet: The former New York City mayor laid out his views on the scope and limits of presidential authority and potential post-Trump curbs.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — If Michael R. Bloomberg is elected president, he says he would be “extremely reluctant” to order the military to attack another country without congressional authorization or an imminent threat to the United States. But he left himself wiggle room, stopping short of saying it would be unconstitutional for him to use force without lawmakers’ approval in other situations.

headline.main: Bloomberg Pledges Restraint on Executive Power but Reserves Legal Wiggle Room
headline.print_headline: Vow of Executive Restraint, With a Bit of Wiggle Room

docs.abstract: President Trump’s border wall is beginning to rise, but a thick curtain of policy changes is more responsible for suppressing the flow of immigrants into the country.
docs.snippet: President Trump’s border wall is beginning to rise, but a thick curtain of policy changes is more responsible for suppressing the flow of immigrants into the country.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s immigration policies — from travel bans and visa restrictions to refugee caps and asylum changes — have begun to deliver on a longstanding goal: Legal immigration has fallen more than 11 percent and a steeper drop is looming.

headline.main: As Trump Barricades the Border, Legal Immigration Is Starting to Plunge
headline.print_headline: Immigration By Legal Path Begins to Fall

docs.abstract: After an airstrike on Turkish forces by Russia or its Syrian allies, President Trump may be forced to pick between Moscow and Ankara.
docs.snippet: After an airstrike on Turkish forces by Russia or its Syrian allies, President Trump may be forced to pick between Moscow and Ankara.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump has long sought to avoid confronting the leaders of Turkey and Russia — two foreign strongmen who are facing off in civil wars in Syria and Libya. But after an airstrike on Thursday that killed dozens of Turkish troops in northwest Syria, Mr. Trump may be forced to pick a side.

headline.main: In Syria and Libya, Trump Is Torn Over 2 Wars, and 2 Strongmen
headline.print_headline: 2 Civil Wars May Force Trump to Choose Between Strongmen

docs.abstract: As time runs out to renew three F.B.I. investigative tools for terrorism and spy inquiries, both parties are divided and President Trump remains a wild card.
docs.snippet: As time runs out to renew three F.B.I. investigative tools for terrorism and spy inquiries, both parties are divided and President Trump remains a wild card.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — An urgent push by Congress to renew several expiring F.B.I. surveillance powers foundered on Wednesday, as House Democrats feuded privately over stronger privacy protections and Republicans remained uncertain about what President Trump, a vocal skeptic of government spying, would accept.

headline.main: Push for More Privacy Protections Throws Surveillance Bill Talks Into Disarray
